  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="vp-section">
    <div class="vp-container vp-narrow">
      <h2 class="vp-h2">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-btn" data-target="faq-1">How long does the full US visa process take from India? <span class="faq-plus">+</span></button>
          <div class="faq-body" id="faq-1"><p>Total timeline: DS-160 (1–2 days) + appointment wait (400+ days standard, 40–60 days express) + post-interview processing (3–15 days). Plan ahead — the appointment is the bottleneck. We help compress this significantly.</p></div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-btn" data-target="faq-2">Can I reapply after a US visa rejection? <span class="faq-plus">+</span></button>
          <div class="faq-body" id="faq-2"><p>Yes. A 214(b) refusal is not a ban. You can reapply immediately. But reapplying with the same profile almost always means another rejection. You need to address the specific gap. Our rejection recovery service handles exactly this.</p></div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-btn" data-target="faq-3">What is the minimum bank balance required? <span class="faq-plus">+</span></button>
          <div class="faq-body" id="faq-3"><p>No fixed minimum. Officers assess your ability to fund the trip and ties to India — income, employment, family, property. A stable income and consistent banking history matter more than a one-time large deposit.</p></div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-btn" data-target="faq-4">What is the DS-160 form? <span class="faq-plus">+</span></button>
          <div class="faq-body" id="faq-4"><p>The mandatory online non-immigrant visa application form issued by the US State Department. Errors here cause complications. We handle DS-160 as part of every full filing service.</p></div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-btn" data-target="faq-5">Can I apply at a consulate outside my home state? <span class="faq-plus">+</span></button>
          <div class="faq-body" id="faq-5"><p>Yes. US consulates are in Mumbai, Delhi, Chennai, Kolkata, and Hyderabad. You can apply at any regardless of residence. We recommend choosing based on appointment availability and approval patterns.</p></div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-btn" data-target="faq-6">What is the difference between B1 and B2 visas? <span class="faq-plus">+</span></button>
          <div class="faq-body" id="faq-6"><p>B1 covers business visits — meetings, training, conferences. B2 covers tourism, family visits, medical treatment. Most Indian applicants receive a combined B1/B2. We recommend applying for the combined unless your purpose is strictly one type.</p></div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-btn" data-target="faq-7">Does prior US travel history improve approval chances? <span class="faq-plus">+</span></button>
          <div class="faq-body" id="faq-7"><p>Significantly. Clean prior US visa history — multiple entries, timely returns — is one of the strongest positive indicators. Bring all old passports with US visas to your interview.</p></div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-btn" data-target="faq-8">Is travel insurance mandatory for a US visa? <span class="faq-plus">+</span></button>
          <div class="faq-body" id="faq-8"><p>Not officially required — unlike Schengen visas. But strongly recommended given the extreme cost of US healthcare. Some officers ask about it. Included in our pre-interview coaching.</p></div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

